tweet_text: These critical bills will enhance the physical, economic, and health resiliency of the Virgin Islands to withstand future climate catastrophes. I will keep fighting every day to help our islands build back better from these storms. (8/8)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: I introduced additional legislation including the Resiliency Enhancement Act, the Territorial Economic Recovery Act, the Territorial Tax Equity and Economic Growth Act, and the Territories Health Equity Act. (7/8)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: I advanced legislation that provided additional support to the Virgin Islands during our recovery by extending Medicaid funding, expanding the child tax credit and earned income tax credit, and temporarily increasing rum tax revenue returned to the VI government. (6/8)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: I advocated with federal agencies to secure funding for recovery efforts in the VI, including $3 billion obligated thus far from FEMA for repair, restoration, and replacement of damaged facilities, and $1.9 billion obligated from HUD for other disaster recovery needs. (5/8)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: Over the past 5 years, I have worked tirelessly to help my home, the Virgin Islands recover and rebuild from these horrific storms and prepare for future climate catastrophes. (4/8)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: The twin devastation from both storms was unprecedented, resulting in at least 5 direct deaths in the Virgin Islands and over $7.5 billion in damage. Communications, transportation, and energy infrastructure shut down and over 90% of buildings in the VI were damaged. (3/8)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: Just two weeks later, on September 20, the U.S. Virgin Islands was devastated by yet another Category 5 storm: Hurricane Maria. With windspeeds reaching 172 MPH, Maria was the strongest and deadliest storm worldwide in 2017. (2/8)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: On September 6, 2017, the U.S. Virgin Islands was hit by Hurricane Irma. With sustained winds speeds of 178 MPH, the National Weather Service confirmed that this Category 5 hurricane was "the strongest hurricane ever observed in the open Atlantic Ocean.‚Äù (1/8)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: On this #EmancipationDay, I am grateful for my ancestors courage and will to be free. we pay homage to our ancestors and reflect on their courageous centuries-long struggle for freedom and equality. (7/7)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text:
Despite the official emancipation in 1848, living conditions for black residents scarcely improved. ¬†
¬†
In 1878, four black women - now known as the ‚ÄòQueens of the Fireburn‚Äô - led a labor riot on St. Croix to demand higher wages and better working conditions. (6/7)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text:
Later that year, 146 enslaved people on St. John revolted. They took control of the island, repelled a counter-invasion, and fought on for 6 months before eventually being defeated. ¬†
¬†
This revolt was the first and one of longest slave rebellions in New World. (5/7)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text:
Enslaved Africans were initially brought to the U.S. Virgin Islands in the late 1600s under brutal conditions.¬†

The 1733 Slave Code on St. John was horrific. Among its punishments, the code ordered that enslaved people who tried to run away would have a leg amputated. (4/7)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text:
Overwhelmed, the Danish colonial Governor Peter von Scholten declared ‚Äúall unfree in the Danish West Indies are from today free.‚Äù¬†
¬†
This freedom was hard-won. (3/7)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text: Slaves around the island e mass organized and marched to the Fort to challenge the Danish rule that kept them in chattel slaver. Demanding freedom against a brutal system ¬†(2/7)

name: Rep. Stacey Plaskett
tweet_text:
July 3 is #EmancipationDay in the U.S. Virgin Islands.¬†
¬†
On this day 174 years ago, in what was then the Danish West Indies, thousands of enslaved people led by their leader General Buddhoe rose up to end slavery on St. Croix. (1/7)

tweet_text: Did you know there are faster ways to return your ballot when you #VoteByMail? If your state has secure designated locations for drop-off, using these will help to ensure that your ballot is received in time to be counted on Election Day.
